    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "f8b6524f_dfb365aa",
        "filename": "/COMMIT_MSG",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 23,
      "author": {
        "id": 1001907
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-01-09T19:45:38Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I\u0027m not an expert in web security, but my understanding is that resources served from the same domain all are considered to be inside the same security domain too. This would mean that any artifacts served from resultdb domain for resultdb\u0027s own purposes would be in the same security domain as any artifact uploaded by a user.\n\nThough maybe artifacts.resultdb.cr.dev would be enough to separate them? I\u0027m thinking about stuff like the githubusercontent.com domain (which is github\u0027s domain for serving user content and is distinct from github.com).\n\nPractically, I think if someone uploaded javascript as an artifact, and then wrote a page which sourced that script from the resultdb domain, that javascript could make XHR requests within resultdb (i.e. execute RPCs) on behalf of the user\u0027s resultdb domain credentials without raising any flags. I think.",
      "parentUuid": "da8df93c_b2f76bda",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 23,
        "startChar": 34,
        "endLine": 23,
        "endChar": 59
      },
      "revId": "156067046ce73e87413a6156ba84bbd86c24f191",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fd06b321_85c32d01",
        "filename": "/COMMIT_MSG",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 32,
      "author": {
        "id": 1001907
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-01-09T18:54:27Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I would note that the opposing groups of properties are\n  * data_stream (which contains its own content_type)\n  * (fetch_url, content_type)\n\nOtherwise multiple artifacts could point to the same data_stream with different content types, which would be weird.\n\nAlso for GCS, doesn\u0027t GCS allow you to set the content type directly already?  (https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/gsutil/addlhelp/WorkingWithObjectMetadata)\n\nIf content_type is just used as a hint for indexing to rdb, maybe it could be reduced to \"index_as\u003dTEXT\" or something like that, and just supplied in conjunction with fetch_url (assuming we want rdb to follow fetch_url via a realm-scoped account and consume that data for indexing). If rdb isn\u0027t going to follow fetch_url itself, then I think content_type probably can just be dropped, and then data_stream would carry its own content_type and index_as flags.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 32,
        "startChar": 14,
        "endLine": 32,
        "endChar": 26
      },
      "revId": "156067046ce73e87413a6156ba84bbd86c24f191",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "8c481f34_76f809ac",
        "filename": "/COMMIT_MSG",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 32,
      "author": {
        "id": 1114299
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-01-09T19:36:28Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "i implied that one cannot specify content type or fetch url if they specify a datastream.\n\n\u003e Also for GCS, doesn\u0027t GCS allow you to set the content type directly already?  \n\nit does. What are you implying?\n\ncontent type is mostly for resultdb clients. We will probably use something more explicit. For BQ export of test results, we explicitly accept BigQueryExports message which explains which test results to export, where to. We can do the same for bigquery export of data streams.",
      "parentUuid": "fd06b321_85c32d01",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 32,
        "startChar": 14,
        "endLine": 32,
        "endChar": 26
      },
      "revId": "156067046ce73e87413a6156ba84bbd86c24f191",
